He is dressed in his immortal grey coat, his leather breecheS, and his big riding boots, soiled with travel; the shapely little feet, of which he was so proud‚ are drawn comfortlessly in; his hat is thrown on the ground. His attitude is that of the deepest dejection and abstraction; his body is sunk and his head seems to bear it down, with its burden of trouble. This is finely indicated by the deep transverse fold of his waistcoat3 one arm is across the back of the chair, the other on his knee‚ his plump hands lying idle 3 his hair, that thiu, black straight hair, looks wet, and lies wildly across his immense forehead. But the face is where the artist has set his highest impress, and the eyes are the wonder of his face.
